occurrences.line_text: That no'te auoyded be by earthly skill or powre.
But all so soone as his outrageous powre
Oppressours powre by armes and puissant hond?
Then is mans body both for powre and forme,
That is her bountie, and imperiall powre,
To serue that Queene with all my powre and might.
This parts great workmanship, & wondrous powre,
But three the chiefest, and of greatest powre,
During which time her powre she did display
And with her powre her owne selfe ouerthrew,
And gainst the Romanes bent their proper powre,
Long mayst thou Glorian liue, in glory and great powre.
As threatning to deuoure all, that his powre despise.
Such wondrous powre did in that staffe appeare,
But wisedomes powre, and temperaunces might,
Not that celestiall powre, to whom the care
For not thy fault, but secret powre vnseene,
Thereat she sighing softly, had no powre
Ybuilded all of glasse, by Magicke powre,
No shadow, but a bodie hath in powre:
Into her former fit; for why, no powre
Ne brauer proofe in any, of thy powre
The powre of forrein Paynims, which inuade thy land.
Shall well defend, and Saxons powre suppresse,
With heauenly powre, and by Angels reskewd,
Or powre, be hable it to remedy,
As ouercomen of the spirites powre,
Both speare & shield of great powre, for her purpose fit.
The mist of griefe dissolu'd, did into vengeance powre.
But them despised all; for all was in her powre.
So feeble is the powre of fleshly arme.
And shewes his powre in variable kinds:
But had no powre in his soft flesh to bite:
Ne suffred she the Middayes scorching powre,
Eternall God in his almighty powre,
Into his powre, that vsed her so hard,
The powre thereof, and lou'd so oft in vaine,
For he the powre of chast hands might not beare,
Well seemes t'exceede the powre of patience,
Sith powre of hand, nor skill of learned brest,
To shew Dan Cupids powre and great effort:
That man and beast with powre imperious
Which did her powre into three parts diuyde;
That neither plate nor mayle, whereas their powre
In which their powre all others did excell;
Much more of price and of more gratious powre
And with vnwearied powre his party still assured.
Ne certes wonder; for no powre of man
Likewise assayd, to proue that girdles powre;
Ne Iudges powre, ne reasons rule mote them restraine.
Whose bodies chast, when euer in his powre
Sith to his powre we all are subiect borne:
Full of sad powre, that poysonous bale did breede
But by the powre of his infectious sight,
And doe dispart the hart with powre extreme,
And tortious powre, without respect or measure.
Left in the victors powre, like vassall bond;
And laid on load with all their might and powre,
Passing the measure of my feeble powre,
When as he saw me, maugre all his powre,
From which vnlesse some heauenly powre her free
The powre to rule the billowes, and the waues to tame.
And inly wish, that in his powre it weare
Whose soueraine powre is herein most exprest,
That powre he also doth to Princes lend,
The club of Iustice dread, with kingly powre endewed.
With wrongfull powre oppressing others of their kind.
Through strong oppression of his powre extort;
That with his powre he all doth ouergo,
But alwaies doe their powre within iust compasse pen.
For wight, against his powre them selues to reare:
All in the powre of their great Maker lie:
He maketh subiects to their powre obay;
For powre is the right hand of Iustice truely hight.
Of womens powre, that boast of mens subiection?
A Princesse of great powre, and greater pride,
Nathlesse for all the powre she did apply,
And though powre faild, her courage did accrew:
In signe of true subiection to her powre,
But if in his owne powre occasion lay,
And eke of powre her owne doome to vndo,
A Goddesse of great powre and souerainty
To shew that she had powre in things diuine;
Such is the powre of that same fruit, that nought
And swolne with pride of his owne peerelesse powre,
That Lion-like shall shew his powre extreame.
Drawne with the powre of an heart-robbing eye,
Such wondrous powre hath wemens faire aspect,
With all their powre, and her full fiercely chast
A Princesse of great powre and maiestie,
And all his powre doth thereunto apply:
Gainst tortious powre and lawlesse regiment,
Purchast through lawlesse powre and tortious wrong
Are dreadded most, and feared for their powre:
With peremptorie powre, that made all mute;
High Gods beheast, and powre of holy lawes;
And high alliance vnto forren powre;
And lastly Griefe did plead, and many teares forth powre.
So much more then is that of powre and art,
But this fell Tyrant, through his tortious powre,
For his huge powre and great oppression,
Through his three bodies powre, in one combynd;
That should their powre against her right oppose.
All to his hands, and gaue him soueraine powre
That by his powre oppressed euery one,
Which towards him with all their powre did ryde,
T'oppose against his powre, he forth issued
Through auarice, or powre, or guile, or strife,
A Lions clawes, with powre and rigour clad,
That sought with lawlesse powre him to oppresse,
Did set vpon those troupes with all his powre and might.
And all his powre applyed thereunto,
Which with strong powre did them long time oppresse;
Did nought regard his malice nor his powre,
Who through stro[n]g powre had now her self in hould,
He spide come pricking on with al his powre and might.
At once did heaue, with all their powre and might,
And with presumpteous powre against that knight streight go'th.
And couching close his speare and all his powre,
And threatning his sharpe clawes, now wanting powre to straine.
Exceeding all the rest in powre and hight;
Small praise to proue your powre on wight so weake.
And him against his powre gan to prepare;
Full in the shield, with so impetuous powre,
Ne powre had to withstand, ne hope of any ayd.
Y e gentle Ladies, in whose soueraine powre
Ne list the Knight the powre thereof assay,
Sitting like King of fowles in maiesty and powre.
Sith in his powre she was to foe or frend;
Faire Pastorella from those Brigants powre,
But aye the more he rag'd, the more his powre increast.
The proued powre of noble Calidore,
And powred forth ouer the Castle wall,
And powred forth his wretched life in deadly dreare.
And powred out of her infernall sinke
Shee smote them lightly with her powrefull wand.
He at his entrance charg'd his powrefull speare
From powrefull eyes close venim doth conuay
Had not the Ladie with her powrefull speach
The vaile, which did his powrefull light empeach;
His powrelesse arme benumbd with secret feare
And bloudie vengeance; lo th'infernall powres
His chaunged powres at first them selues not felt,
All other powres and knighthood he did scorne.
Therefore, deare Sir, your mightie powres assay.
Were cleane consum'd, and all his vitall powres
To rest them selues, and weary powres repaire,
Who when their powres, empaird through labour long,
That all his manly powres it did disperse,
But either hellish feends, or powres on hie:
And doubling all his powres, redoubled euery stroke.
That vitall powres gan wexe both weake and wan,
Vnited all his powres to purge himselfe from blame.
The which the powres to thee are pleased to reuele.
Of secret things, and all the powres of nature,
Ne felt his blood to wast, ne powres emperisht,
And all her vitall powres with motion nimble,
Priuily pricked with thy lustfull powres,
Are not all places full of forraine powres?
Oftimes their sundry powres they did employ,
And powring forth their bloud in brutishe wize,
And powring balme, which he had long puruayd,
His poynant speare, that many made to bleed,
With that his poynant speare he fierce auentred,
With dreadfull poyse is from the mayneland rift,
What was the poyse of euery part of yore:
And through his soule like poysned arrow perst,
That all mine entrailes flow with poysnous gore,
Ne poysnous Enuy iustly can empaire
But noysome breath, and poysnous spirit sent
Out of her poysnous entrails, fraught with dire decay.
As doth the poysnous sting, which Infamy
The poysnous humour, which did most infest
And poures his poysnous gall forth to infest
His poysnous point deepe fixed in his hart
A floud of poyson horrible and blacke,
And secret poyson through their inner parts,
Was swolne with wrath, & poyson, & with bloudy gore.
And learne from pleasures poyson to abstaine:
In poyson and in bloud, of malice and despight.
Till that through poyson stopped was his breath;
Pouring out streames of poyson and of gall
And rayl'd and rag'd, till she had all her poyson spent.
Most vgly filth, and poyson therewith rusht,
The bloudie gore and poyson dropping lothsomely.
Foming with poyson round about her gils,
Did sharpen them, and in fresh poyson steepe:
But he the more his wicked poyson forth did poure.
Contagious poyson close through euery vaine,
That spat out poyson and gore bloudy gere
And spitting forth the poyson of his spight,
When him the poysoned garment did enchaunt
But toades and frogs, his pasture poysonous,
Full of sad powre, that poysonous bale did breede
His practick wit, and his faire filed tong,
In cunning sleights and practick knauery.
Wherein she vsed hath the practicke paine
Right practicke was Sir Priamond in fight,
And practicke vse in armes: ne spared not
For both were wondrous practicke in that play,
Therein well practisd was, and in the same
That through continuall practise and vsage,
Too rathe cut off by practise criminall
But he him selfe, through practise vsuall,
Least any more such practise should proceede.
The plot of all her practise did display,
Sometime the fawne I practise from the Doe,
To practise games, and maisteries to try,
Which in her cot she daily practised.
For whom he could not kill, he practizd to entrap.
And perfectly practiz'd in womans craft,
And with them practiz'd, how for to depryue
Ne ought ye want, but skill, which practize small
And humbly praid to let them in that night:
Vnmou'd with praiers, or with piteous thought,
Th'end of his drift, he praisd his diuelish arts,
Escaped hardly, hardly praisd his wedlock good.
Liagore, much praisd for wise behests;
Beseeching him with prayer, and with praise,
Great paines, & greater praise, both neuer to be donne.
At last yledd with farre reported praise,
And draw them from pursuit of praise and fame,
Against his praise to stirre vp enmitye
His be the praise, that this atchieu'ment wrought,
All vertue merits praise, but such the most of all
True be thy words, and worthy of thy praise,
Vnmindfull of thy praise and prowest might,
And then due praise, or due reproch them yield;
First praise of knighthood is, foule outrage to deface.
With these in praise of pollicies mote striue.
Their minds to praise, and cheualrous desire:
To pricke of highest praise forth to aduance,
Of sleeping praise, were hong vpon a tree,
From seeking praise, and deeds of armes abrode,
To hunt for glorie and renowmed praise;
But all for praise, and proofe of manly might,
Doth praise thee oft, and oft from Stygian deepe
And crowne of heauenly praise with Saints aboue,
Euen immortall praise, and glory wyde,
Which much augmented all their other praise.
But all the more, the more his praise increst.
And make his praise before his owne preferd:
That with the praise of armes and cheualrie,
Of beauties praise, and yeeld the fayrest her due fee.
But she with blame would blot, & of due praise depriue.
That all men much admyrde her change, and spake her praise.
Both of their publicke praise had them despoyled,
And knights of Maidenhead, whose praise she would empaire.
That all his former praise doth fowly spill.
To see the man, whose euerlasting praise
That all my former praise hath blemisht sore;
The goodly praise of Princely curtesie,
Yet praise likewise deserue good thewes, enforst with paine.
Small praise to proue your powre on wight so weake.
And praise the feature of her goodly face,
Some praise her paps, some praise her lips and nose;
Some praise her paps, some praise her lips and nose;
What haue I, but to praise th'Almighty, that doth send it?
The more t'augment her price, through praise of comlinesse.
And spake the praises of the workmans wit;
And antique praises vnto present persons fit.
That all your other praises will deface,
Well may ye speed in so praiseworthy paine:
For praising loue, as I haue done of late,
And did her greatly like, and did her greatly praize.
Some prancke their ruffes, and others trimly dight
In sumptuous tire she ioyd her selfe to prancke,
As Peacocke, that his painted plumes doth prancke,
Full farre was I from thinking such a pranke;
Feigning full many a fond excuse to prate,
So did the villaine to her prate and play,
And towardes him with dreadfull fury praunce;
When vnder him he saw his Lybian steed to praunce.
All were it Zeuxis or Praxiteles:
As Lyon fierce vpon the flying pray,
Your first aduenture: many such I pray,
But to the pray when as he drew more ny,
Where that old woman day and night did pray
Which hardly doen, at length she gan them pray,
And still amidst her rayling, she did pray,
Her selfe a yeelded pray to saue or spill.
And him rencountring fierce, reskewd the noble pray.
As when a Gryfon seized of his pray,
And now the pray of fowles in field he lyes,
From Lyons clawes to pluck the griped pray.
The innocent pray in hast he does forsake,
Her hoped pray, she would no lenger bide,
Fast flying from the Paynims greedy pray,
The pitteous pray of his fierce crueltie haue bin.
The knight then lightly leaping to the pray,
So brought vnto his Lord, as his deserued pray.
And well begun end all so well, I pray,
With Vnaes foe, that all her realme did pray.
And euer vp to heauen, as she did pray,
And made him pray both earely and eke late:
But first thou must a season fast and pray,
Which as an Eagle, seeing pray appeare,
To trusse the pray too heauie for his flight;
And gan to highest God entirely pray,
It booted nought to thinke, to robbe him of his pray.
And for his safetie gan deuoutly pray;
Whom they in equall pray hope to deuide,
Whom raging windes threatning to make the pray
She would admit, albe the knight her much did pray.
Thy carcasse for their pray, the guerdon of thy paine.
Should be his pray. And therefore still on hye
And grieu'd, so long to lacke his greedy pray;
Of grace I pray thee, giue to eat and drinke to mee.
So goodly did beguile the Guyler of the pray.
The world with murdrous spoiles and bloudie pray,
Against his foe and mine: watch thou I pray;
If it be I, of pardon I you pray;
Were to those Pagans made an open pray,
That deepe engorgeth all this worldes pray:
Dare not aduenture on the stubborne pray,
And yield the pray of loue to lothsome death at last.
(For what doest not thou know?) of grace I pray,
Thou then shalt make, t'increase thy louers pray.
Few dayes before, had gotten a great pray
Whether more happie were, to win so goodly pray.
Do one, or other good, I you most humbly pray.
The Monster ready on the pray to sease,
Him forst to leaue his pray, for to attend
But trembled like a lambe, fled from the pray,
But trembling stood, and yielded him the pray;
Haue care, I pray, to guide the cock-bote well,
The greedy villein from his hoped pray,
Distaynd with durt and bloud, as relique of the pray.
Pardon I pray my heedlesse ouersight,
Your countrey kin, and you entirely pray
Waiting aduauntage on the pray to sease;
But weete henceforth, that all that golden pray,
Fame is my meed, and glory vertues pray.
But those two sought nought, but the present pray,
To blot her with dishonor of so faire a pray.
Faire Sir, of friendship let me now you pray,
Lo sluggish Knight the victors happie pray:
The couenant was, that euery spoyle or pray
As when a Vulture greedie of his pray,
To rescue Satyrane out of his pray;
I me submit, and you of pardon pray,
Ne care he had, ne pittie of the pray,
Who trussing me, as Eagle doth his pray,
Defends him selfe, and saues his gotten pray.
So tempting her still to pursue the pray,
Forgoe the purchase of my gotten pray,
Does make her selfe misfortunes piteous pray.
The other stayd behind to gard the pray.
Yet my good lucke he shall not likewise pray;
And like a greedie Beare vnto her pray,
And of his innocence to make her pray.
Are met at spoyling of some hungry pray,
But he like hound full greedy of his pray,
Saying, Sir Knight, of pardon I you pray,
Which brought that Damzell, as his purchast pray;
Till he himselfe was made their greedie pray,
And all her pray, and all her diet know.
Forst to forgoe his pray there in the place,
Like to a Tygre that hath mist his pray,
Wherewith the beast enrag'd to loose his pray,
The litle babe, sweet relickes of his pray;
And plucke the pray oftimes out of their greedy hould.
In that good Hermits charge, whom he did pray
Thereto, when needed, she could weepe and pray,
And of the pray each one a part doth beare.
Amongst the rest, the which they then did pray,
Mote them descry, nor reskue from their pray,
Hither those Brigants brought their present pray,
Of all the other pray, which they had got,
The greatest portion of the greedie pray;
Disperseth them to catch his choysest pray;
And therefore them of patience gently prayd.
But like so as the rest he prayd for nought,
Then they Malbecco prayd of curtesy,
And therefore prayd her wake, to heare him plaine.
But he her prayd, for mercy, or for meed,
Like as his mother prayd the Destinie,
All on her gazing wisht, and vowd, and prayd,
But her of pardon prayd more earnestlie,
From day to day she woo'd and prayd him fast,
She often prayd, and often me besought,
And streight that boaster prayd, with whom he rid,
The more that he with meeke intreatie prayd,
And prayd the place of her abode to learne.
Chyld Tristram prayd, that he with him might goe
Receiued had, and prayd to pitty his ill plight.
And often him besought, and prayd, and vowd;
And softly whispering him, entyrely prayd,
But holding vp his hands, with silence mercie prayd.
They prayd high God him farre from them to send.
They prayd him sit, and gaue him for to feed
And therefore prayd, that those same captiues there
Tho Coridon he prayd, sith he well knew
For thy I may not graunt, that ye so greatly prayde.
His Loues deare spoile, in which his heart was prayde,
And all the way he prayed, as he went,
And her to saue from outrage, meekely prayed him.
Beseeching him with prayer, and with praise,
Allured be, for prayer nor for meed.
That to his prayer nought he would incline,
But when she saw her prayers nought preuaile,
Her prayers nought preuaile, his rage is more of might.
Thou doest the prayers of the righteous sead
Or by good prayers, or by other hap,
Ne would for price, or prayers once affoord,
Vnto the Church, their prayers to appeale,
Amongst her teares immixing prayers meeke,
And with her prayers reasons to restraine
Vnto her selfe her silent prayers did impart.
With humble prayers and intreatfull teares;
Drew to the gate, and there with prayers meeke,
And called oft with prayers loud and shrill,
Vnto her prayers piteously enclynd,
Which booted nought for prayers, nor for threat
Of fowles and beastes he made the piteous prayes,
With warlike spoiles, and with victorious prayes,
But praying still did wake, and waking did lament.
As that in stead of praying them surcease,
So praying him t'accept her seruice euermore.
And therein he likewise was praying now,
Now praysd, hereafter deare thou shalt repent:
Then God she praysd, and thankt her faithfull knight,
Of marchants farre, for profits therein praysd,
And litle prays'd his labours euill speed,
He praysd it much, and much admyred it;
It answered was, her name was Prays-desire,
Much can they prayse the trees so straight and hy,
Of brothers prayse, to you eke longs his loue.
For all for prayse and honour he did fight.
But friendly each did others prayse deuize
A worke of labour long, and endlesse prayse:
That I note, whether prayse, or pitty more:
So double was his paines, so double be his prayse.
Ne ought the prayse of prowesse more doth marre,
Till it the pitch of highest prayse exceeds:
Such prayse is shame; but honour vertues meed
The Maide[n]; proud through prayse, and mad through loue
Both loosers lot, and victours prayse alsoe.
Famous throughout the world for warlike prayse,
In rule succeede, and eke in fathers prayse;
A woman worthy of immortall prayse,
O famous moniment of womens prayse,
Who in all godly thewes, and goodly prayse
To sing his mistresse prayse, and let him mend,
That in their proper prayse too partiall bee,
That now we foolish men that prayse gin eke t'enuy.
Be thou faire Britomart, whose prayse I write,
O soueraigne Queene, whose prayse I would endite,
The greater Britaine, here to seeke for prayse and fame.
Which through the earth haue spred their liuing prayse,
Of gods high prayse, and of their loues sweet teene,
The prayse of her fresh flowring Maidenhead;
In so great prayse of stedfast chastity,
And both encreast the prayse of woman kind,
Ne euer cast his mind to couet prayse,
Then enterprised prayse for dread to disauaunce.
And, that augmented all her other prayse,
The prayse of prowesse from them all away.
But second vnto none in prowesse prayse;
But all that day the greatest prayse redounded
As it is greater prayse to saue, then spill,
Who then can thee, Mercilla, throughly prayse,
But thine owne people do thy mercy prayse much more.
As prayse and honour? Or is ought so bright
Of all those goodly implements of prayse,
And vnderneath thy feete to place her prayse;
As thy great iustice praysed ouer all:
Much more it praysed was of those two knights;
That such proud looks would make her praysed more;
Whose prayses hauing slept in silence long,
Led with thy prayses and broad-blazed fame,
And staynd their prayses with thy least good part;
Far reach her mercies, and her prayses farre,
O who can tell the prayses of that makers might!
Which yet their prayses speake, all be they loth,
Bad counsels, prayses, and false flatteries.
Thy selfe thy prayses tell, and make them knowen farre.
Your curteous tongue, his prayses to compile,
The prayses of high God he faire displayes,
His mistresse prayses, sweetly caroled,
Sith all thy worthy prayses being blent,
The prayses of that Prince so manifold:
The which did pype and sing her prayses dew,
Of his owne vertues, and prayse-worthy deedes.
Praysing their god, and yeelding him great thankes,
Lauding and praysing his renowmed worth,
That euer she sees doen prays-worthily,
Ne I against the same can iustly preace:
And all that preace did round about her swell,
What meant that preace about that Ladies throne,
Exceld at Athens all the learned preace,
And as she passed through th'vnruly preace
And thrusting fierce into the thickest preace,
And round about him preace in riotous aray.
And pressing through the preace vnto the gate,
Which with great vprore preaced to draw nere
And heauenly documents thereout did preach,
And preacht the truth, but since it greatly did decay.
Then preacing to the pillour I repeated
Farre from all peoples prease, as in exile,
